The data in data(Monks) are âlikeâ and âdislikeâ nominations by 18 monks living in the same monastery over three time periods. Therefore the observed variables are counts from 0 to 3 of times monk A nominated monk B as liked or disliked.1 Each row in the data is a pair of monks (a dyad). The variables are: â¢ A: Index number for first monk in dyad â¢ B: Index number for second monk in dyad â¢ like_AB: Number of times A nominated B as liked â¢ like_BA: Number of times B nominated A as liked â¢ dislike_AB: Number of times A nominated B as disliked â¢ dislike_BA: Number of times B nominated A as disliked

Problem 01

  1. Use these data to estimate the amount of reciprocity in âlikeâ nominations within dyads. You can ignore the âdislikeâ data for now. Use the social network example from the book to help, but you should modify it appropriately.
data(Monks)
d <- Monks %>% rename(D = dyad_id) %>% mutate(Y=3L) %>% as_tibble()
head(d)

$$ \[\begin{align} L_{AB} &\sim \text{Bernoulli}(3, p_{AB}) \\ \log(p_{AB}) &= \alpha + T_{AB} \\ L_{BA} &\sim \text{Bernoulli}(3, p_{BA}) \\ \log(p_{BA}) &= \alpha + T_{BA} \\ \begin{pmatrix} T_{AB} \\ T_{BA} \end{pmatrix} &\sim \text{MVNormal}( \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} \sigma^2 & \rho\sigma^2 \\ \rho\sigma^2 & \sigma^2 \end{bmatrix} ) \\ \rho &\sim \text{LKJCorr}(2) \\ \sigma &\sim \text{Exponential}(1) \\ \alpha &\sim \text{Normal}(0,1) \end{align}\] $$

N_dyads <- nrow(d)
d_list <- d %>% as.list()
d_list$N_dyads <- N_dyads

m1 <- ulam(
  alist(
    like_AB ~ binomial(Y, pAB),
    like_BA ~ binomial(Y, pBA),
    logit(pAB) <- alpha + T[D,1],
    logit(pBA) <- alpha + T[D,2],
    alpha ~ normal(0, 1),
    
    ## Dyad effects
    transpars> matrix[N_dyads, 2]:T <- 
      compose_noncentered( rep_vector(sigma_T,2) , L_Rho_T , Z ),
    matrix[2, N_dyads]:Z ~ normal(0,1),
    cholesky_factor_corr[2]:L_Rho_T ~ lkj_corr_cholesky(2),
    sigma_T ~ exponential(1),
    
    ## compute correlation matrix dyad
    gq> matrix[2,2]:Rho_T <<- Chol_to_Corr(L_Rho_T)
  ),
  data = d_list, chains=4, cores=4, iter=2000
)

Now also analyze the âdislikeâ nominations. Estimate the amount of reciprocity in the âdislikeâ nominations and compare to the estimate from the âlikeâ nominations. Does âlikeâ or âdislikeâ have higher reciprocity? Be sure to compute the posterior contrast between the two estimates.

Problem 03

Now consider generalized liking and disliking. Add generalized âreceivingâ parameters to the model, analogous to receiving varying effects from the sharing example in the book/lecture. (Each monk only named 3 likes and 3 dislikes each time, so the amount of âgivingâ is fixed by design in these data.) Can you identify any individuals who are particularly liked/disliked, independent of the dyadic relations?

N_dyads <- nrow(d)
d_list <- d %>% as.list()
d_list$N_dyads <- N_dyads
d_list$M <- c(d_list$A, d_list$B) %>% unique() # Monk

m3 <- ulam(
  alist(
    like_AB ~ binomial(Y, pAB),
    like_BA ~ binomial(Y, pBA),
    logit(pAB) <- alpha + T[D,1] + R[B],
    logit(pBA) <- alpha + T[D,2] + R[A],
    alpha ~ normal(0, 1),
    
    ## Monks effect
    R[M] ~ normal(alpha_M, sigma_M),
    alpha_M ~ normal(0,1),
    sigma_M~ exponential(1),
    
    ## Dyad effects
    transpars> matrix[N_dyads, 2]:T <- 
      compose_noncentered( rep_vector(sigma_T,2) , L_Rho_T , Z ),
    matrix[2, N_dyads]:Z ~ normal(0,1),
    cholesky_factor_corr[2]:L_Rho_T ~ lkj_corr_cholesky(2),
    sigma_T ~ exponential(1),
    
    ## compute correlation matrix dyad
    gq> matrix[2,2]:Rho_T <<- Chol_to_Corr(L_Rho_T)
  ),
  data = d_list, chains=4, cores=4, iter=2000
)

N_dyads <- nrow(d)
d_list <- d %>% as.list()
d_list$N_dyads <- N_dyads
d_list$M <- c(d_list$A, d_list$B) %>% unique() # Monk
N_monks <- d_list$M %>% length()
d_list$N_monks <- N_monks

m4 <- ulam(
  alist(
    # Like
    like_AB ~ binomial(Y, pAB),
    like_BA ~ binomial(Y, pBA),
    logit(pAB) <- alpha + T[D,1] + R[B,1],
    logit(pBA) <- alpha + T[D,2] + R[A,1],
    alpha ~ normal(0, 1),
    
    #Dislike
    dislike_AB ~ binomial(Y, pABd),
    dislike_BA ~ binomial(Y, pBAd),
    logit(pABd) <- alpha_d + Td[D,1]+ R[B,2],
    logit(pBAd) <- alpha_d + Td[D,2]+ R[A,2],
    alpha_d ~ normal(0, 1),
    
    ## Monks effect
    vector[2]:R[N_monks] ~ multi_normal(0, Rho_M, sigma_M),
    Rho_M ~ lkj_corr(4),
    sigma_M~ exponential(1),
    
    ## Dyad effects - Like
    transpars> matrix[N_dyads, 2]:T <- 
      compose_noncentered( rep_vector(sigma_T,2) , L_Rho_T , Z ),
    matrix[2, N_dyads]:Z ~ normal(0,1),
    cholesky_factor_corr[2]:L_Rho_T ~ lkj_corr_cholesky(2),
    sigma_T ~ exponential(1),
    
    ## Dyad effects - Dislike
    transpars> matrix[N_dyads, 2]:Td <- 
      compose_noncentered( rep_vector(sigma_Td,2) , L_Rho_Td , Zd ),
    matrix[2, N_dyads]:Zd ~ normal(0,1),
    cholesky_factor_corr[2]:L_Rho_Td ~ lkj_corr_cholesky(2),
    sigma_Td ~ exponential(1),
    
    ## compute correlation matrix dyad
    gq> matrix[2,2]:Rho_T <<- Chol_to_Corr(L_Rho_T),
    gq> matrix[2,2]:Rho_Td <<- Chol_to_Corr(L_Rho_T)
  ),
  data = d_list, chains=4, cores=4, iter=2000
)

  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:N_monks) +

  labs(title="Raw", y="odds") +
  theme_light()
